  "text": "The G1 garbage collector's concurrent marking and mixed collection cycle in OpenJDK is implemented through the following key components and their execution flow:\n\n## G1ConcurrentMark Start Trigger\n\nThe concurrent marking cycle is triggered by the Initiating Heap Occupancy Percent (IHOP) mechanism. In `src/hotspot/share/gc/g1/g1Policy.cpp`, the `G1Policy::need_to_start_conc_mark()` function (line 745) checks if the current heap occupancy has exceeded the marking threshold returned by `G1IHOPControl::get_conc_mark_start_threshold()` (defined in `src/hotspot/share/gc/g1/g1IHOPControl.hpp` line 62). When the threshold is exceeded, `G1Policy::decide_on_concurrent_start_pause()` (line 1223) calls `G1Policy::initiate_conc_mark()` (line 1218) to set the `in_concurrent_start_gc` flag, which triggers the concurrent marking cycle initiation during the next safepoint.\n\n## Concurrent Marking Cycle Phases\n\nOnce initiated, the concurrent marking cycle is orchestrated by `G1ConcurrentMarkThread::run_service()` in `src/hotspot/share/gc/g1/g1ConcurrentMarkThread.cpp` (line 115). The cycle follows these phases:\n\n1. **Concurrent Cycle Start**: `G1ConcurrentMark::concurrent_cycle_start()` in `src/hotspot/share/gc/g1/g1ConcurrentMark.cpp` (line 1114) initializes the marking bitmap and prepares data structures.\n\n2. **Mark Loop**: Executed by `G1ConcurrentMarkThread::concurrent_mark_cycle_do()` (line 271), which includes:\n   - Root region scanning via `G1ConcurrentMarkThread::phase_scan_root_regions()` (line 171)\n   - Mark from roots via `G1ConcurrentMark::mark_from_roots()` (line 1145)\n   - Remark pause via `G1ConcurrentMark::remark()` (line 1380)\n\n## SATB Marking Queue Processing\n\nDuring the concurrent marking phase, the Snapshot-At-The-Beginning (SATB) write barriers record references in per-thread marking queues. The `G1SATBMarkQueueSet::filter()` function in `src/hotspot/share/gc/g1/g1SATBMarkQueueSet.cpp` (line 116) processes these queues during the remark phase. The `requires_marking()` helper function (line 82) determines whether entries in the SATB buffer require marking by checking if they are below the Top-At-Mark-Start (TAMS) pointer and have not already been marked.\n\n## Remembered Set Scanning and Selection\n\nAfter marking completes, the cycle enters the rebuild and cleanup phase. The `G1ConcurrentMark::rebuild_and_scrub()` function in `src/hotspot/share/gc/g1/g1ConcurrentMark.cpp` (line 1406) calls `G1UpdateRegionLivenessAndSelectForRebuildTask` (defined at line 1203), which iterates over heap regions and determines which old and humongous regions should be included in the mixed collection based on liveness information collected during marking.\n\nRegion selection is driven by `G1RemSetTrackingPolicy::update_old_before_rebuild()` and `G1RemSetTrackingPolicy::update_humongous_before_rebuild()` in `src/hotspot/share/gc/g1/g1RemSetTrackingPolicy.cpp` (lines 70 and 49 respectively). These methods evaluate region liveness and remembered set states to determine if regions should be selected for reconstruction and potential mixed collection inclusion.\n\n## Mixed Collection Region Selection\n\nThe final step in the concurrent marking cycle is selecting candidate regions for mixed collection. The `G1CollectionSetChooser::build()` function in `src/hotspot/share/gc/g1/g1CollectionSetChooser.cpp` (line 262) performs a parallel scan of the heap to identify candidate regions and prunes them based on the G1HeapWastePercent threshold. These candidates are then passed to `G1CollectionSetCandidates::set_candidates_from_marking()` in `src/hotspot/share/gc/g1/g1CollectionSetCandidates.cpp` (line 282), which organizes them into collection groups for staged evacuation during subsequent mixed garbage collection pauses.\n\nThe remembered set scanning infrastructure is implemented through the `G1RemSetScanState` class in `src/hotspot/share/gc/g1/g1RemSet.cpp` (line 89), which manages the state of card table scanning during evacuation and coordinates the work distribution for parallel remembered set processing.\n\nThis integrated flow ensures that G1 maintains a continuous cycle of concurrent marking, liveness analysis, and region selection to drive efficient incremental garbage collection with low pause times."
